Part 2

The hospital corridor smelled of Dettol, floor bleach, and overcooked rice from the visitors' canteen downstairs. Vikram found his father's room by counting the doors along the corridor, refusing to ask the busy nurses at the main station. 

His father was not sitting up in bed, reading files or shouting commands at the office staff. That version of the scene had existed only in the imaginations Vikram had built on the overnight passenger train from college.

The real scene: Binay Ahuja lay propped on two flat, yellowed pillows, his skin having gone the dull color of weak tea. A saline tube was taped crookedly into the back of his right hand, the plastic bag dripping slowly above the iron bedframe. 

He was awake, his eyes fixed on the wooden door.

"You came," Binay said, his voice dry and raspy. It was not a question.

"Papa," Vikram said, standing near the foot of the bed.

"Sit."

Vikram sat on the low wooden stool beside the bedside cabinet. For a long time, neither of them said the thing that needed saying; instead, they said the small, empty things that fill the space before it.

"Rohan ate?" Binay asked, looking toward the window.

"I don't know, Papa. I came straight from the station."

"Someone should check on him. He's at home."

"I'll check," Vikram said.

"Sit first," Binay said, his hand twitching slightly on the sheet.

Vikram sat back down. A young resident doctor came in, flipped the cardboard chart hanging from the bed rail, and spoke. 

He used words like *portal hypertension* and *we'll monitor* and *let's see how he responds to the diuretics* in the calm, rehearsed tone doctors use when they don't yet know which sentence they'll have to say next week. 

Vikram, now six months into his second year of medicine, understood exactly enough of the words to know that "not knowing" was the actual diagnosis. 

The resident doctor left, his stethoscope tapping against his hip. Binay watched him go, his eyes narrowing slightly.

"He talks like your college professors," Binay said, his lips thin. "Confident about being unsure."

"That's the job, Papa. Medicine is like that sometimes."

"It was going to be your job too."

Vikram said nothing. He looked at the white walls, where the paint had started peeling near the ceiling fan.

"I told Sharma-ji at the club last year," Binay said, his voice dropping. "'My son, wait and watch, one day he will be a big doctor.' I said it like the degree was already sitting in my pocket. Like a pocket watch."

He looked at the saline line in his own hand, studying the tape as if it belonged to someone else. "Seems fate had a different item in that pocket."

"Papa, don't talk like that—"

"I'm not being dramatic, Vikram. I'm being accurate," Binay said.

A heavy silence settled in the room, carrying the weight of unsaid things. Then Binay did something Vikram had never expected; he looked almost embarrassed, his eyes shifting away from his son's face.

"I have to ask you something," Binay said, "and I don't like asking it."

"Ask, Papa."

"Can you stay here for some weeks? Just to look after things at the office. Nothing big. Just sign what Pradhan-babu tells you to sign."

Binay coughed, his hand going to his side. "Rohan is sixteen, still in school. He can't be at the plant every day, and the distributors are starting to make noise."

"Some weeks," Vikram repeated, his throat dry.

"That's all I'm asking," Binay said, closing his eyes.

It did not feel like all he was asking. It felt like the first sentence of something much longer, spoken deliberately small so that it could be agreed to without fear.

Vikram said yes anyway. What else does a nineteen-year-old say to a father with a tube taped to his hand and skin the color of weak tea.

---

Pradhan-babu turned out to be sixty-one years old, wore the same brown wool cardigan every day regardless of the heat, and had worked for Binay Ahuja since before Vikram was born. 

His office was a single small room with one ceiling fan missing a blade, which made the whole ceiling shake, and a typewriter that jammed every time he hit the letter 'M'.

"Sign here, sign here, and here," Pradhan-babu told Vikram on the first morning. He slid three thick green ledgers across the wooden desk.

Vikram took the pen and signed his name quickly.

"Not like that," Pradhan-babu said, pointing with a ruler.

"Like what?"

"Full signature. Vikram Ahuja. Not initials. The bank won't accept initials from a new signatory on the account."

Vikram signed again, slower this time. The letters came out wrong-sized and shaky, a schoolboy's handwriting trying to look official. 

Pradhan-babu watched him do it twice more before the signature looked acceptable. He didn't comment; he just took the ledgers back, blew the dust off the edges, and refiled them in the steel cabinet.

At noon, a factory supervisor from the malt unit came to the office, twisting his cloth cap in both hands, waiting to speak to "Ahuja Sahib." 

Vikram stood up to greet him properly, the way he had been taught to greet a senior doctor doing rounds in the hospital. "Sir," Vikram said, before he could stop himself.

The supervisor blinked, his face confused. He looked behind him to check who Vikram was addressing, but nobody was there.

Pradhan-babu spoke from his desk, without looking up from his typewriter. "You're Ahuja Sahib now, Vikram. People say sir to you. Not the other way."

The typewriter jammed at that exact moment. The 'M' key locked mid-stroke, the carriage refusing to advance.

Pradhan-babu picked up his wooden ruler without any change in expression, tapped the side of the typewriter mechanism twice—not hard, but with the precision of a man who has found the exact spot—blew into the small space between the keys, and pressed the 'M' twice more to confirm it had returned to service.

Then he resumed typing, exactly where he had stopped, as if this had not happened.

Vikram felt his ears go warm, the exact same warmth he had felt on the staircase at college when the seniors had laughed at his name. He stood up straight, clearing his throat.

"Yes," Vikram said to the supervisor, trying to keep his voice steady. "Tell me. What's the problem at the malt unit?"

It was better. Not good, but better.

---

Some weeks became six weeks. Six weeks became a semester he didn't return for. 

Binay Ahuja came home from the hospital thinner than before and walking slower, but he was home. The crisis, whatever it truly was, had loosened its grip without fully letting go.

His father never again mentioned the boy who was going to wear a white coat. Vikram never again mentioned the exams he had missed, or the ones after that. 

Some things are easier to leave unfinished than to formally end. The Pathology textbook stayed behind in the hostel cupboard two hundred kilometers away, in room twenty-four, where neither of them thought about it often.

The signature got better and faster. The word "sir" stopped catching in Vikram's throat. 

Within a year, nobody in that dusty office remembered that he had ever hesitated at the desk. Vikram remembered, but he just stopped mentioning it to anyone.

[End of Part 2]
